WEBVTT

00:03.445 --> 00:05.695
- I can't eat any more.
- Come on. Just a few more bowls.

00:05.789 --> 00:07.088
Mom said we had to
finish the whole thing

00:07.190 --> 00:08.810
before we could cut
the record off the box.

00:08.882 --> 00:10.248
<i>For breakfast back in the '70s,</i>

00:10.350 --> 00:11.983
<i>parents put their trust in any tiger,</i>

00:12.086 --> 00:13.885
<i>Cap'n or chocolate vampire</i>

00:13.987 --> 00:15.620
<i>who'd fill their kids with enough sugar</i>

00:15.723 --> 00:16.922
<i>to send them bouncing out of the house</i>

00:17.024 --> 00:18.423
<i>until the street lights came on.</i>

00:18.525 --> 00:20.926
- Mornin', gents.
- Hey, you want some cereal?

00:21.028 --> 00:23.195
- What record's on the box?
- "Sugar, Sugar" by the Archies.

00:23.297 --> 00:24.629
Get back to me when it's Zeppelin.

00:24.698 --> 00:26.164
I just walked by Mom and Dad's door.

00:26.266 --> 00:27.866
Lots of whispering going on.

00:27.968 --> 00:29.768
Probably a grown-up matter
that's none of our business.

00:29.870 --> 00:31.303
Hmm.

00:35.109 --> 00:37.175
<i>Nowadays, parents tend to
include their little darlings</i>

00:37.277 --> 00:39.177
<i>in every discussion,
no matter how intimate...</i>

00:39.279 --> 00:40.879
<i>drugs, illness, why Mommy</i>

00:40.981 --> 00:42.647
<i>goes on solo trips
with her personal trainer...</i>

00:42.750 --> 00:44.983
<i>But in 1972, my folks practiced</i>

00:45.085 --> 00:47.352
<i>the "none of your beeswax"
approach to parenting.</i>

00:47.454 --> 00:49.488
I'm so nervous. My hands are shaking.

00:49.590 --> 00:51.089
Pretty sure that's the sugar.

00:51.191 --> 00:52.624
Well, we better go find Eddie then.

00:52.726 --> 00:54.326
Bail, bail, bail, bail!

00:55.591 --> 00:58.505
<font color="#0080ff">Synced & corrected by</font> kinglouisxx
<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

00:58.565 --> 00:59.865
Your mom and I are going out.

00:59.967 --> 01:01.066
You have to keep an eye on the baby.

01:01.168 --> 01:02.134
I'm kind of busy.

01:02.236 --> 01:03.268
Unless that rest of that sentence

01:03.370 --> 01:05.003
is "finding a new place to live," here.

01:08.575 --> 01:10.542
Weekday morning and Dad's missing work?

01:10.644 --> 01:12.778
He didn't even do that
when William was born.

01:12.880 --> 01:15.280
I remember. It hurt my feelings.

01:15.382 --> 01:18.150
And Mom never leaves the house
unless it's an emergency.

01:18.252 --> 01:19.951
Maybe the house is on fire.

01:20.053 --> 01:21.486
No, they'd at least take the baby.

01:21.588 --> 01:23.321
And they'd tell us.

01:23.423 --> 01:24.990
Probably.

01:25.092 --> 01:26.792
We need to get to the bottom of this.

01:26.817 --> 01:27.949
You two, come with me.

01:27.988 --> 01:29.855
- William, stall them.
- How?

01:29.957 --> 01:31.390
Just hold their attention for a minute.

01:31.492 --> 01:33.058
I couldn't even do that by being born.

01:33.160 --> 01:35.093
It's go time. Let's do this.

01:35.195 --> 01:36.895
Oh, um, hey! Hey!

01:36.997 --> 01:39.120
I was wondering if I could
ask you guys something.

01:39.183 --> 01:41.617
- What?
- Uh...

01:41.719 --> 01:46.021
This whole Vietnam quagmire,
I mean, how do we get out of that?

01:48.025 --> 01:49.692
- I'm gonna suffocate!
- You're small.

01:49.794 --> 01:51.861
You don't need much air.
Just keep your ears open.

01:51.963 --> 01:53.329
I can breathe through my ears?

01:53.431 --> 01:55.431
If you get caught,
this is all your idea.

01:55.533 --> 01:58.033
They know I don't have ideas.

01:58.136 --> 01:59.702
That kid is weird.

01:59.804 --> 02:02.104
- He just reads too much.
- Tell him to knock it off.

02:02.206 --> 02:03.439
We'll be back later.

02:03.541 --> 02:05.141
Try not to read while we're gone.

02:05.241 --> 02:06.733
Okay.

02:08.112 --> 02:11.147
No! No, no, no!
Get down, get down, get down!

02:11.249 --> 02:13.382
Looks like another blessing from God.

02:13.484 --> 02:15.050
Mm-hmm.

02:15.153 --> 02:17.553
Maybe you'll finally get
that girl you always wanted.

02:17.655 --> 02:19.155
That'd be nice.

02:19.257 --> 02:21.524
Ran out of boys' names
I liked four kids ago.

02:21.626 --> 02:23.559
Wasn't Pat supposed to be Pete?

02:23.661 --> 02:26.328
I was so loopy on those drugs,
I spelled it wrong.

02:26.430 --> 02:28.664
By the way, I want those drugs again.

02:28.766 --> 02:31.300
Sleeping through it really made
the whole experience special.

02:31.402 --> 02:33.202
Oh, it'll be special either way.

02:33.304 --> 02:35.304
I mean, we're welcoming
another blessed bundle.

02:35.406 --> 02:37.540
Well, Peggy.

02:37.642 --> 02:39.875
False alarm. Sorry to say
you're not expecting.

02:39.977 --> 02:42.178
Yes!

02:42.280 --> 02:43.679
Whoo!

02:46.284 --> 02:49.351
Guess we weren't so happy about
another blessed bundle.

02:49.453 --> 02:51.487
I was happy,

02:51.589 --> 02:56.325
but now I'm happy in
a different... happier way.

02:58.296 --> 03:00.196
How's your day goin', pal?

03:05.503 --> 03:07.236
Come on, hon.

03:07.338 --> 03:09.338
You must be a little relieved.

03:10.675 --> 03:12.441
I am.

03:12.543 --> 03:14.610
You disappointed you're not
gonna get those drugs anymore?

03:14.712 --> 03:16.879
I still have to have that cyst
removed, so I'll get the drugs.

03:16.981 --> 03:18.113
Mm.

03:18.284 --> 03:20.851
No, I'm just surprised.

03:20.953 --> 03:22.586
I thought we both wanted this,

03:22.688 --> 03:24.621
and the truth is, neither of us did.

03:24.723 --> 03:27.157
How many kids have we
been pretending that for?

03:27.259 --> 03:28.825
I'd like to hear your number first

03:28.928 --> 03:30.661
in case it's smaller than eight.

03:30.763 --> 03:32.696
- I'm kidding.
- Is it weird

03:32.798 --> 03:34.531
you and I have never really talked

03:34.633 --> 03:36.333
about how many kids we wanted?

03:36.435 --> 03:38.802
We put more discussion
into buying a new toaster.

03:38.904 --> 03:41.004
Well, a toaster is something
you can do something about.

03:41.106 --> 03:42.472
Kids just happen.

03:42.574 --> 03:44.274
At least for us.

03:46.545 --> 03:47.844
Should've gone with
the four-slice toaster.

03:47.947 --> 03:49.513
I know. I'm kicking myself.

03:50.616 --> 03:53.350
This operation, it's really necessary

03:53.452 --> 03:55.185
or is it one of those scams
like when they wanted

03:55.287 --> 03:57.521
- to take out Eddie's appendix?
- Well, it's a benign cyst,

03:57.623 --> 03:58.822
but I guess it is necessary,

03:58.924 --> 04:01.091
since it's what caused the false alarm.

04:01.193 --> 04:03.472
At least I'll get to be in
the hospital for three days.

04:03.552 --> 04:04.644
Are you worried?

04:04.714 --> 04:08.316
About my house being torn
to pieces while I'm gone.

04:10.369 --> 04:12.002
As long as you'll be okay.

04:12.104 --> 04:13.537
I should be fine.

04:13.639 --> 04:16.005
You heard Doctor Shaff.

04:16.108 --> 04:17.507
It's just a little cyst.

04:20.389 --> 04:23.055
Mom said we're having a little sister!

04:27.104 --> 04:29.166
- Are you sure?
- That's what Mom said.

04:29.245 --> 04:32.221
- A little sister.
- So irresponsible.

04:32.299 --> 04:34.274
Our resources
are overstretched as it is.

04:34.345 --> 04:35.945
Mom and Dad should've
stopped plopping out babies

04:36.014 --> 04:38.381
- three kids ago. Nothing personal.
- No, I get it.

04:38.483 --> 04:40.516
The problem is, they love
each other very much,

04:40.585 --> 04:42.485
and when two people love
each other, babies come.

04:42.587 --> 04:45.021
- Or when they're just bored.
- I like having a little sister.

04:45.089 --> 04:47.623
We can be like Jody and Buffy
on "Family Affair."

04:47.725 --> 04:49.158
They're not really brother and sister.

04:49.227 --> 04:50.860
- They're just actors.
- Yeah, and so fake.

04:50.962 --> 04:52.528
I mean, TV does that all the time.

04:52.630 --> 04:53.763
Kids who look nothing alike

04:53.865 --> 04:55.665
pretending to be the same family.

04:55.767 --> 04:57.900
Guys, I just thought of another problem.

04:58.002 --> 04:59.902
Girls need privacy.

05:00.004 --> 05:02.238
She's gonna need her own room.

05:02.340 --> 05:04.607
Buffy can sleep with Mom.

05:04.709 --> 05:07.209
And Dad can move into our bedroom!

05:07.311 --> 05:09.078
We have to bunk with Dad?

05:09.180 --> 05:10.880
I hate Buffy.

05:10.982 --> 05:13.449
You're right. It's not a great name.

05:13.551 --> 05:15.184
I'm gonna go think of a better one.

05:15.286 --> 05:17.520
I-I think maybe we should run
this by Eddie and Lawrence.

05:18.656 --> 05:22.658
But now that I'm here,
you're glad, right?

05:24.162 --> 05:25.327
Sure.

05:26.397 --> 05:27.563
You're gonna have to step up

05:27.665 --> 05:29.165
feeding those kids while I'm away.

05:29.267 --> 05:31.100
Oh, yeah, you're gonna need
more milk for breakfast.

05:31.169 --> 05:32.702
I just bought eight half-gallons.

05:32.804 --> 05:34.036
It'd be cheaper to buy a cow.

05:34.138 --> 05:35.337
Well, maybe Pat would finally shut up

05:35.406 --> 05:36.639
about that dog he wants.

05:36.741 --> 05:37.840
They like Pop-Tarts and Eggos, too,

05:37.942 --> 05:39.041
but you'll have to toast those...

05:39.143 --> 05:40.276
two at a time.

05:40.378 --> 05:41.510
Okay, there's plenty of stuff in here

05:41.612 --> 05:43.012
for three days worth of dinners.

05:43.114 --> 05:44.814
Monday night is frozen pizza
and tater tots,

05:44.916 --> 05:46.782
but don't give Pat any pizza
until he finishes all his tots.

05:46.884 --> 05:49.552
No way she's expecting.
Pat must've heard wrong.

05:49.654 --> 05:52.288
Plus, doctors can't even tell
it's a girl until it's born.

05:52.356 --> 05:54.523
If Mom was expecting, I would know.

05:54.625 --> 05:56.492
I've got my ear pressed to the ground.

05:56.561 --> 05:58.394
And your nose pressed
to Mom and Dad's butts.

05:58.496 --> 06:00.362
Oh, yeah? Better than you having yours

06:00.431 --> 06:02.431
pressed to their, uh... to their...

06:02.533 --> 06:05.034
To... To their what?

06:05.103 --> 06:06.435
You got nothing.

06:06.537 --> 06:08.137
Yeah, if you guys
are worried about this,

06:08.239 --> 06:09.772
you should just ask Mom.

06:09.874 --> 06:11.207
You know, she's very approachable.

06:11.309 --> 06:12.441
No, we can't ask them.

06:12.543 --> 06:13.876
This is delicate stuff.

06:13.945 --> 06:15.344
They wouldn't tell us the truth anyway.

06:15.446 --> 06:17.079
They think if we have
too much information,

06:17.181 --> 06:19.515
we might rise up against them.

06:19.617 --> 06:21.117
And they're not wrong.

06:23.187 --> 06:25.721
Apparently, Pat has some
cockamamie shrimp allergy,

06:25.823 --> 06:28.357
so if you open a can of that
Chun King Shrimp Chow Mein,

06:28.459 --> 06:29.625
he only gets a small portion.

06:29.727 --> 06:31.193
Allergies.

06:31.295 --> 06:33.329
I don't know where these doctors
come up with this stuff.

06:33.431 --> 06:34.897
You know, Mike,

06:34.999 --> 06:36.565
I've been thinking about

06:36.667 --> 06:39.135
how we don't want another kid right now.

06:39.237 --> 06:40.970
There might be a way
to be smart about it.

06:41.072 --> 06:42.872
Honey, we're not allowed
to be smart about it.

06:42.950 --> 06:43.908
We're Catholics.

06:43.994 --> 06:47.647
Right, but there are some things
we can do and not do.

06:47.712 --> 06:50.513
I hope you're not suggesting
what I think you're suggesting.

06:50.615 --> 06:54.784
Because I like it, and it's
free, so I'm not giving it up.

06:54.886 --> 06:56.552
I like that it's free, too.

06:56.654 --> 06:57.921
We wouldn't have to give anything up.

06:57.999 --> 06:59.989
Just plan ahead and schedule it.

07:00.091 --> 07:02.057
I'll grab the TV Guide.

07:02.160 --> 07:04.860
We can see if there's any duds
on "Carson" next week.

07:04.962 --> 07:06.962
It's about my schedule, not Johnny's.

07:07.064 --> 07:09.198
There's certain days out of the
month where I'm more likely...

07:09.300 --> 07:10.966
Oh, I see where this is going.

07:11.068 --> 07:12.368
You already get the one week off,

07:12.470 --> 07:14.036
and now you want to add black-out days.

07:14.138 --> 07:15.871
I'm trying to stick to
the Church's rules.

07:15.973 --> 07:17.373
If it were up to me,
we could try some of these new

07:17.475 --> 07:19.341
tricks everyone's talking about.

07:19.443 --> 07:21.243
You know, it's not just
rubbers anymore, Mike.

07:21.345 --> 07:25.014
They've got cups and rings
and pills and hoops.

07:25.116 --> 07:27.049
I mean, the Protestants
have a whole magic show

07:27.151 --> 07:29.185
- going on down there.
- And they're having a pretty good time,

07:29.287 --> 07:31.053
- but we know better.
- Do we?

07:31.155 --> 07:32.721
I get it. The Pope wants more Catholics,

07:32.824 --> 07:35.324
but we've already given them
almost a whole baseball team.

07:36.427 --> 07:37.593
Guys! Guys! Guys!

07:37.695 --> 07:39.128
I have fresh intel.

07:39.230 --> 07:41.197
Mom is going away for three days.

07:41.299 --> 07:42.726
Three days?!

07:42.781 --> 07:44.335
Oh, and we're having lasagna on Tuesday.

07:44.402 --> 07:47.039
What? Lasagna is a weekend food.

07:47.117 --> 07:48.316
None of this makes any sense.

07:48.418 --> 07:50.051
Where would Mom go for three days?

07:50.153 --> 07:51.419
And once she's seen the outside world,

07:51.521 --> 07:53.021
why would she ever come back?

07:53.123 --> 07:55.223
They're in the bedroom right now
talking about it.

07:56.459 --> 07:59.027
I feel like I'm sinning just
having this conversation.

08:01.564 --> 08:03.598
I need to go to Confession.

08:03.700 --> 08:05.033
That's a thought.

08:05.135 --> 08:06.634
I'll take this up with Father Dunne.

08:06.736 --> 08:08.169
Maybe there's an option
we haven't thought about...

08:08.271 --> 08:10.438
one they only give you
if you make a fuss.

08:10.540 --> 08:12.674
I'll bet he'll side with
the Pope on this one.

08:12.776 --> 08:14.575
He knows where his bread is buttered.

08:16.446 --> 08:18.479
I-I'm gonna kill you!

08:18.581 --> 08:20.648
- You're choking me to death!
- Take it outside.

08:25.422 --> 08:26.821
Eddie, we're going to Confession.

08:26.923 --> 08:29.290
- Watch the baby.
- I'm on the case.

08:29.392 --> 08:31.025
You don't always have to say
things in a weird way.

08:31.127 --> 08:32.460
Aye aye, Mom!

08:32.562 --> 08:33.895
So, what do we know?

08:33.996 --> 08:35.730
Pat heard something he didn't understand

08:35.832 --> 08:37.932
and Mom's going away for three days.

08:38.034 --> 08:39.866
Don't forget weekday lasagna.

08:39.970 --> 08:42.203
I told you, the lasagna's a blind alley.

08:42.304 --> 08:43.837
And now they're going to Confession

08:43.940 --> 08:45.440
to talk things over with Father Dunne.

08:45.508 --> 08:48.209
Then we need ears inside
that confessional.

08:48.311 --> 08:49.978
It's time.

08:50.080 --> 08:51.646
We'll use the kit.

08:53.650 --> 08:55.016
What kit?

08:55.841 --> 08:57.018
- Wow!
- Wow!

08:57.120 --> 08:58.853
<i>It was Joey's spy kit.</i>

08:58.955 --> 09:00.888
<i>Everything we needed to crack
this case wide-open...</i>

09:00.991 --> 09:02.323
<i>invisible ink, a periscope,</i>

09:02.392 --> 09:03.691
<i>a gun that turned into a camera,</i>

09:03.793 --> 09:05.026
<i>a camera that turned into a gun,</i>

09:05.128 --> 09:07.428
- <i>and best of all...</i>
- Disguises?!

09:07.530 --> 09:08.830
Okay, where'd you get this?

09:08.932 --> 09:11.199
Deals were made. Grades were changed.

09:11.267 --> 09:12.926
Let's just say if Scotty Stancroft

09:12.989 --> 09:16.771
ever actually becomes a doctor,
I wouldn't let him cut <i> me</i> open.

09:16.873 --> 09:19.440
<i>Funny story... Scotty Stancroft
actually did become a doctor</i>

09:19.509 --> 09:21.275
<i>and he ended up on "20/20."</i>

09:28.952 --> 09:31.085
I've spotted the subject's car.

